"I will just wait here then."
"Great. Just follow me, like always."
"Not very much. It seems that the enemy used some old, abandoned mines and had some excavation done to house the army."
"When you began to explore the caves and wreak havok on parts of the army, the enemy collapsed the tunnels leading to his main base. That's all I know. So, ready to go then?"
"I hope you are getting closer to becoming the Lord of the Keep. How can I help you?" Alias grins as you approach.

value.0: "Are you ready to return to the keep, <FirstName>? I can bring you back here again, if you wish."
"Good. Follow me."
Alias is a cute, young woman with a perpetual smirk and a twinkle in her eye.
"Good day. When I was told to help you, I quickly sketched a map of the keep. There you go."
"I also know my way around the countryside and some of the caves, as I am one of the local scouts. I am proud to be working with a hero such as yourself."
"I will do all I can to help you attain Lordship of the Keep. My first suggestion is that you visit the guildmasters. Do you have questions for me?"
"Good luck. Come speak to me if you would like a guide to take you outside the city. I will stay by the fountain in the market square until you need me."
"Wait! I haven't told you about my Aunt Serah yet. Would you like me to tell you about a quick, easy way to make some gold, gain a vote and earn yourself more time for the election?"
She looks a little surprised. "Oh, sorry. I thought it might be useful information for you."
"Good luck. Come speak to me if you would like a guide to take you outside the city. I will stay here until you need me."
"It is both my job and my pleasure. The keep already pays me, so I can help you for free. Where would you like to go?"

"If you're just looking for stuff to do, the Guildhall's always a good place to start. Besides, I never turn down a chance to poke my nose into my Aunt Serah's business and see what she's up to. And The Stan's always fun to talk to, too."
"The Stan is the master of the trades guild. He's unusual, but he usually all manner of crazy quests that he wants people to do for him."

"He pays pretty well, too, which is always nice. Of course, there are other guildmasters in the Guildhall, too, and then some others that are spread around the keep, so you could just explore if you wanted to."
"Right away, m'<Lord/Lady>."

"Archeologists are funny, always digging around in the dirt for something that everybody's already forgotten about. I say if we forget something happened, there's probably a good reason for it. But that's just my opinion. I'll take you there pronto."
"I'm glad we found those because I hear he had enough in store to lay a fair-sized siege. Come on, I'll take you there."

"Dwarves are so industrious. It's a shame about the air quality, though. I wouldn't be able to live a day if all there was to smell was dust and dwarves... But enough of my blather. I'll take you right there."
"Wow, the old ruins have always given me the heebie jeebies. My aunt says there was some powerful magic there once. I'll take you right there but there's no way I'm going inside!"
"Just a hop, skip and a jump, but watch that last jump or you'll get lost." She grins and laughs as she runs off, beckoning you to follow.
"Great! Follow me and try to keep up!"
"That's what I'm here for. What would you like to know about?"
"Is there anything else you need, m'<lord/lady>?"
"Other than the caves, there isn't too much to talk about. There is a Hermit who keeps bees and sometimes sells their honey. Haven't seen him around in a while though."
"Sometimes we get a caravan just outside the main gates. Hopefully there wasn't one there when the attack began, or they'll all be dead now."
"Other than that, there isn't a lot other than some hunting and the odd monster. Anything else?"
"That is too bad. He was strange, but likable enough. Sad about the honey too; he always had the best."
"That is wonderful. He always has the best honey!"
"What does he need help with?"

value.0: "I could do that. I am always looking to make a little extra gold on the side. He really didn't seem to be a bad guy and I loved his honey."
"There are quite a few caves near here, and ever since the army disappeared with Lord Keldrick, monsters have begun to make them their homes."
"I imagine that is where the army of creatures came from. Something powerful and intelligent must be driving them to work together. Normally they just fight each other."
"I can lead you to specific caves, but it helps if you know which ones you want to go to."
"The keep is broken up into two main sections. The Gates of Cyan is where most of the fighting took place. It opens into the South Keep, where the majority of the townspeople live and work."

"The North Keep is where the wealthier townsfolk live and includes the Temple and the Silver Lily Inn. If you don't want to pay the extra cost for room charge, you might consider the Mossy Tree in the South Keep."
"The North Keep also holds our Guildhall where the Banner, the Hand and the Lord all live, as well as where the guild offices are. Do you need anything more specific?"
"There are plenty of tasks that need done, but the best place for adventurers to find work is at The Trades, in the Guildhall. The Stan can probably line up some jobs for you."
"You will need to find a room to stay in. The Mossy Tree Inn is a cheaper place to stay, but still good quality, or if you have a little more coin to spend, The Silver Lily is a very nice inn."
"I would suggest the Temple of the Nine Gods, in the North Keep. I am sure they could help you out."
"There are numerous stores and merchants around here. You might want to try the Pawnshop, the Smithy, the Quartermaster, Yenna's Tower or even the Temple."
"Just wander around and I'm sure you'll find what you need."
"There are nine guilds, each headed by a man or woman who is outstanding in their specialty. For example, my Aunt Serah is the guildmaster of the landowners."

"She owns some of the most productive farmlands in the area. I'll tell you right now that if you prove yourself by destroying some of the monstrous army that attacked us, she would likely vote for you."
"She always favors deeds over words, so along with my recommendation, I'm sure you will have her vote. The rest of the guildmasters are a different story, but you'll manage. All you need is time."
"Enivid would seem to be the obvious choice to become the Lady of the Keep, but she has alienated a lot of us. Her strict rules and obsession with order have caused many hard feelings."
"The truth is, I think she scares people. Nobody can live up to her ideal, so they are nervous around her, waiting to be judged."
"Having said that, the gods know you couldn't be much worse than Sir Becket!"
"Sir Becket is a corrupt, craven, coward! He will drain the resources of the keep and flee the next time we are attacked."
"No. I have only what I can see and hear. But as I am a scout, those are the senses that keep me alive. All my instincts tell me that he is a monster. You must be better than him."
"If the election were held right now, you would lose. People need to get to know you... to trust you. They would follow Enivid, because they know and respect her."
"They might follow Sir Becket, because he has had time to fool some and to control others. You are the wild card. You really need time."
"I really don't pay much attention to politics. I try to spend as much time outside the keep as possible."
"The best person to ask is probably Momma Dane. She spends most of her time helping others in the keep and she loves to talk. I'm sure she would love to tell you what you want to know."
"She is usually in the marketplace, where people can easily find her if they need help."
"The nine guildmasters will meet in the castle, where they will each cast a stone; a different color for each of the contestants. The person with the most votes wins."
"So you need at least four votes, with no other opponent getting more than three. You have chosen the most difficult path, but it certainly has the greatest reward."
"Oh, and I should tell you, the more votes you get, the more secure your position will be, but don't try to get them all, or people will become suspicious. Just a suggestion."
"I understand. If you want to move around the countryside quickly, come back and speak to me. Otherwise, god speed."
"I will do my best. What would you like?"
"I will do my best, though politics are not one of my strengths. The most important thing you need is time to gain votes over your competitors. What would you like to know?"
"Aunt Serah is a very earthy woman. She has lands just outside of town. She has been asking for help from the military guild for almost a year now."
"There is a cave on her property that some goblins moved into. Unfortunately the military has been weak since Lord Keldrik left with most of our army."
"If you were to get rid of the goblins for her, I'm sure Aunt Serah would support your cause. I can even lead you to the caves myself."
"I suppose there are probably things you need to do first. Did you have other questions?"
"She has offered a bounty of 200 gold for the clearing of the caves. That would be yours, besides the vote. She might also give you something even more precious... time."
"If they hold the election right away, you might not have time to sway enough votes. Aunt Serah's guild usually votes together on an issue to decide how my aunt should vote."
"If you solve my aunt's problem, I am sure she would be willing to slow down the vote by holding off the landowner's guild vote."
"You should be. I can tell you that right now, you wouldn't even likely get a single vote. Nobody knows you yet. Time is your worst enemy right now."

"Unless you don't really care about winning the election... ha, ha, ha. As if anyone would turn down the Lordship of a castle, plus the income, plus the lands, and the fame that would come with the position."
"I mean, who knows... a good lord could expand our borders... conquer other territories... maybe even become a king."
Alias sighs and looks at the ground. "I don't know what drives you, so maybe I should tell you what drives me."
"The people here are not all good people, nor all bad people. Despite their many strengths, many are easily duped into following someone who looks noble, like Sir Becket."
"Others are impressed by the noble carriage of someone like Enivid. But neither choice is the right one. Who knows, maybe you aren't the right one either."
A tear forms in the corner of Alias's eye. "I guess I was wrong about you then. Do as you will."
"What do you need of me?"
"Sir Becket is thoroughly corrupt and he is a craven coward. He will drain the resources of this keep and then flee when danger comes."
"Enivid has good intentions, but her view of the world is too limited. She can't see any shades of gray."

"I don't know why you are having such difficulty with becoming a leader, but I simply have a feeling that you are the one we need. Perhaps you believe I am just a foolish child, but I am more than that."
"Allow me to help you. You can be more than this. You could be the <Lord/Lady> we have been searching for. All you have to do is try."
"I guess I don't! You are a bitter disappointment! What would you have of me then?"
"There is always choice. I just hope you will make the right one. So would you like to go to the caves or did you have more questions?"
"That is all anyone can ask. So would you like to go to the caves or did you have more questions?"
"I know you are a paladin too, but you have seen more of the world than Enivid has. You can make difficult choices that I don't think Enivid can. At least I hope so."
"Then we need to focus on making you the perfect <lord/lady>. First, you need my aunt to buy you some time."
"Yes, but first you need to solve her little problem. Would you like me to take you to the caves?"
"Aunt Serah is a woman of actions over words. If you do the job for her, then speak to her, she'll be more impressed."
"Great! Follow me and try to keep up!"
"Though it hardly seems worth our effort to bother with such base creatures, I suppose it would go well towards furthering our popularity."
"I would free the land of these creatures, even if it is to help a farmer. Goblins are a foul abomination and horridly ugly... not that I am one to speak."
"Goblins? Even Trip can kill nasty, ugly goblins! We will sneak up on them and tear out their throats, we will!"
"Goblins! Time to crush some skulls, <FirstName>! We shall revel in their destruction and win the hearts of these people, you and I!"
"She's a very powerful woman in these parts. I'm certain if you deal with the goblins on her land and bring her back proof of the deed, you'd win her vote for the election, easy!"

"Goblins tribes tend to rely pretty heavily on their Chief. If you can kill the Chief, the tribe usually scatters and gets absorbed into other neighboring tribes. It may sound grisly but the head of the Goblin Chief would probably be all the evidence you need."
"She really appreciates how you dealt with those goblins on her property. You're guaranteed her vote, that's for sure!"
"You want to know about me? I'm not really that exciting, I'm afraid. My Aunt Serah is a guildmaster, which is as close to fame as I get. What did you want to know about me?"
"That would be good. What would you like to know?"
She blushes lightly. "It is more of a childhood nickname. I was always pretending to be a spy and I would tell people 'That's not my name. My alias is...' and then I would use a word I liked."
"Alias Nefarious, alias Rogue, alias Insidious... all of the largest or most colorful words I could find. People gave up trying to remember them and just decided to call me Alias."
She hesitates. "I really don't like it. I much prefer Alias, please."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> She looks down at her feet, scuffing the dirt, then mumbles, 'Bertha Blackhand'."
She flushes red and glares at you. "I'll thank you not to repeat that. Now let's not talk about me anymore."
"Thank you. Even my father called me Alias."
"You are a liar, but thank you. I won't answer to it though, so don't even try. I am Alias... even my father called me that."
"I was just born to it, I think. Even when I was only ten and my father was still around, I would wander outside the keep by myself."
"I would get in a lot of trouble for doing that, so I learned how not to get caught. That skill has saved my life many times over the years."
"Once I reached an age where people started taking me seriously, I spoke to the Banner and he allowed me to prove myself and join the guard."
"Yes, yes, staying hidden, a very important skill it is."
"You know, you kind of scared me at first, but now I think you're kind of cute."
"Cute? Trip is not cute! You should not say such things. Trip is fearsome! Trip is terrifying... or was that terrified? Terrific? Oh, now Trip is confused."
"Well, I think you're cute."
<StartAction>[Mutter]</Start> "Stupid humans!"
"I grew up here in the keep. My father was a soldier in Lord Kendrick's army, and I guess he must have died when they went to war."
"My mother died when I was young. She caught a cold one winter and started coughing very hard. She coughed up blood for a long time and then one morning the house was silent."
"My Aunt Serah, guildmaster for the landowners, took me in and raised me. She was always kind, but firm and hard working."
"I... I am sorry. I guess I don't really know anything about you. My father was a kind and loving man. A lot of families lost children or spouses."
"I am used to it, thank you very much! I am not complaining, just explaining. My biggest wish is that I could know what really happened to my father."
"Really? Maybe that is why I feel such a bond with you. I have felt like I could trust you from the moment you arrived."
"I just wish I knew what happened to my father. He and the other soldiers went riding off to war, but never showed up for the battle. No one has seen or heard a trace of them."
"Thank you. I just wish I knew what happened to my father. He must be dead, but how or when or where... nobody knows. A lot of families lost children or spouses."
"Nobody ever found out where they went. They went riding off to war, but never showed up for the battle. No one has seen or heard a trace of them."
"But enough about the dead. My Aunt Serah really took good care of me, when I was young. Now I am a scout for the keep. The pay is alright, and at least the work isn't monotonous."
"There must have been some powerful magic involved in making an entire army disappear! It is unnatural."
"Armies don't just disappear! This sounds like some sort of foul magic. We need to be wary."
"Trip knew a halfling once who could make a pig disappear! But it was only a trick. Nothing but powerful magic could make an army disappear."
"There is something familiar about this tale, like a legend I once read... but I cannot place it. We should keep our eyes and ears open for some kind of magic around the keep... something old."
"That reminds me. You should go and speak to The Stan, at the Trades office. He needs somebody to help an archeologist who was studying the magic of the keep."
"Who knows how this could help you? The magic might give you the power to stop the invaders. Then people would have to vote for you, wouldn't they?"
"The ruins he was investigating seem to be protected by undead. He needs someone to help him get past them."

value.0: "Oh, <FirstName>, I have a message for you. A very... strange message." Alias' face is paler that you remember and her lips are pursed in a look of bewildered concern.
"I'm sorry, <FirstName>! I hadn't heard that you won, but congratulations! I wonder if that is linked to the message... I guess it must be."
"It was Momma Dane. One minute I was chatting with her, and then all of a sudden she began to laugh maniacally."
"She leaned over and said, 'Tell my grandchild that the throne is not secure until the illithid is dead.' I asked her who she meant but she just winked and pointed towards the castle."
"Then she suddenly stood up straight and her body changed. She grew young and beautiful and she had wings. As she flew away, she cried, 'Tell <FirstName> to look for me when the battle is won!"
"Oh, I didn't think you would have a clue of what I was talking about. I'm impressed."
"I know, it must seem strange. As she floated away, I heard her laugh and say 'Oh, <FirstName>, you are everything I hoped for, and then some.'"
"As she floated away, I heard her laugh and say 'Oh, <FirstName>, you are everything I hoped for, and then some.'"
"Be careful, <FirstName>, Momma Dane wanted you to become the <Lord/Lady> of the Keep. She must have something planned."
"I will remain here, in case you need me to take you anywhere else. Congratulations... my <lord/lady>. I always had faith in you!"
"There was always something unnatural about that woman, yet it seemed ridiculous to mention it at the time. Now I wish I had."
"This woman had wings, but whether she is a creature of good or evil, Trip is unsure."
"All I ever sensed was a strong desire to see you on the throne of the keep, <FirstName>. I have no idea if she had plans beyond that."
"That has a strangely ominous ring to it."

This should occur when the PC gains another vote after the second. Have a few triggers placed in common areas that the PC will have to cross fairly frequently. Have the triggers check how many votes the pc has, and if the vote has been postponed on this number of votes. ie. Alias will only do this once when the third vote is gained, etc.
The PC can only postpone the vote 3 times, so the most votes they should be able to get is six. After the sixth vote is gained, the PC will have to go to the election.
When this is triggered, freeze the PC's movement, have Alias jump to the PC and initiate conversation. WE don't want the PC to miss the fact that she is there.
